<%- include('partials/header.ejs') %>

<section class="stage-banner">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="stage-header">
            <div>
                <p class="section-label">Stage Three</p>
                <h1 class="section-title">Treatment Options & Government Funding</h1>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row align-items-center">
            <div class="col-md-8">
                <p class="section-intro">
                    Once your investigative cycle is complete and a diagnosis 
                    (or unexplained infertility) has been established, your specialist will discuss 
                    treatment options. In 2025, the Ontario government announced a 
                    <a href="https://news.ontario.ca/en/release/1006038/ontario-helping-more-families-access-fertility-supports" 
                       target="_blank" class="green-text" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" 
                       title="Source: Ontario Newsroom, June 2025">$250 million investment</a> 
                    to expand fertility services across the province through the 
					Ontario Fertility Program (<span class="navy-text">OFP</span>). Here is an overview of the most common 
					treatment paths and what is covered.
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4 text-center desktop-img">
                <img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/Ontario_buliding.jpg" 
                     alt="Ontario government fertility program announcement" 
                     style="max-width: 100%; border-radius: 8px;">
            </div>
			<div class="row align-items-start">
				<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/treatment_planning.png" 
					alt="Illustration of a fertility treatment calendar and medical chart" 
					style="max-width: 100%; border-radius: 8px;">
			</div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<%- include('partials/stage3-options') %>

<section class="section-light">
	<div class="container">

		<!-- Option1: Ovulation induction -->
		<div class="info-block" id="ovulation-induction">
			<h4>Ovulation Induction + Timed Intercourse</h4>
			<div class="row align-items-start">
				<div class="col-md-4 text-center mb-3 order-md-2">
					<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/ovulation_treatment.png" 
						alt="Ovulation induction illustration" 
						style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 250px; border-radius: 8px;">
				</div>
				<div class="col-md-8 order-md-1">
					<p>
						This is often the first treatment your doctor will suggest. You take oral 
						medication (such as Clomid or Letrozole) to stimulate your ovaries to 
						produce one or more eggs, then time intercourse around your fertile window. 
						Your clinic will monitor your cycle with ultrasounds and blood work to 
						pinpoint the best timing.
					</p>
					<p>
						This approach is commonly recommended for patients with irregular ovulation 
						or unexplained infertility, as long as both fallopian tubes are open and 
						sperm quality is normal. If it does not result in pregnancy after a few 
						cycles, your doctor will typically recommend moving to IUI or IVF.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="highlight-box">
				<strong>Ovulation induction with timed intercourse is not funded under the OFP.</strong>
				<ul class="highlight-box_list">
					<li>Clinic visits, ultrasounds, and blood work for monitoring are covered 
						by OHIP.</li>
					<li>Medications are <b class="navy-text">not covered</b> and vary in cost 
						depending on whether your doctor prescribes oral medication or 
						injectable hormones.</li>
					<li>Some private insurance plans may cover a portion of fertility 
						medications. You can also claim these costs through the Ontario 
						Fertility Treatment Tax Credit.</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</div>


		<!-- Option2: IUI -->
		<div class="info-block" id="iui">
			<h4>IUI (Intrauterine Insemination)</h4>
			<div class="row align-items-start">
				<div class="col-md-4 text-center mb-3 order-md-2">
					<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/iui_treatment.png" 
						alt="IUI illustration" 
						style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 250px; border-radius: 8px;">
				</div>
				<div class="col-md-8 order-md-1">
					<p>
						IUI is the most common form of 
						<span class="ohip-tip" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" 
							title="Artificial Insemination (AI): a broader term for transferring sperm into the vagina or cervix. IUI is a more targeted version where sperm is placed directly into the uterus.">artificial insemination (AI)</span>. 
						During an IUI procedure, sperm is collected, washed, and concentrated in 
						the lab to select the healthiest cells. The processed sample is then 
						injected directly into your uterus using a thin catheter, timed to 
						coincide with ovulation. The procedure itself takes only a few minutes 
						and is done at your fertility clinic. IUI may be done with or without 
						ovulation-stimulating medications, depending on your diagnosis.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="highlight-box">
				<strong>IUI is fully funded under the Ontario Fertility Program (OFP).</strong>
				<ul class="highlight-box_list">
					<li>No limit on the number of IUI cycles you can receive.</li>
					<li>The insemination procedure, cycle monitoring, ultrasounds, and blood work are covered.</li>
					<li>Sperm washing (sperm preparation) is <b class="navy-text">not covered</b>. 
						Some clinics charge around <span class="orange-text">$775 per cycle</span>, 
						but prices vary by clinic.</li>
					<li>IUI can be done with or without fertility medications.</li>
					<li>If your doctor prescribes medications, those are also 
						<b class="navy-text">not covered</b> and cost approximately 
						<a href="https://www.ontario.ca/page/get-fertility-treatments" target="_blank" 
						class="green-text" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" 
						title="Source: Ontario Ministry of Health">
							<span class="orange-text">$1,000 or more per cycle</span></a>
							depending on the type and dosage of medication prescribed. 
						These costs may be partially covered by private insurance or claimed 
						through the Ontario Fertility Treatment Tax Credit.</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</div>


		<!-- Option3: IVF -->
		<div class="info-block" id="ivf">
			<h4>IVF (In Vitro Fertilization)</h4>
			<div class="row align-items-start">
				<div class="col-md-4 text-center mb-3 order-md-2">
					<img src="<%= basePath %>/static/images/ivf_treatment.png" 
						alt="IVF illustration" 
						style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 250px; border-radius: 8px;">
				</div>
				<div class="col-md-8 order-md-1">
					<p>
						IVF is a more involved process where eggs are retrieved from your ovaries, 
						fertilized with sperm in a lab, and the resulting embryo is transferred back 
						into your uterus. It is typically recommended when IUI has not been successful, 
						or when your diagnosis requires it.
					</p>
					<p>Here is what the process generally looks like:</p>
					<ul>
						<li><strong>Ovarian stimulation:</strong> daily hormone injections for about 
							10 to 14 days to stimulate your ovaries to produce multiple eggs. During 
							this time, you will visit the clinic frequently for blood work and 
							ultrasounds to monitor your response.</li>
						<li><strong>Egg retrieval:</strong> a short procedure done under sedation 
							where eggs are collected from your ovaries using a thin needle guided 
							by ultrasound.</li>
						<li><strong>Fertilization:</strong> your eggs are combined with sperm in the 
							lab. In some cases, your doctor may recommend 
							<span class="ohip-tip" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" 
								title="Intracytoplasmic Sperm Injection: a single sperm is injected directly into each egg. Often recommended when sperm count or motility is low.">ICSI</span> 
							to improve fertilization rates.</li>
						<li><strong>Embryo development:</strong> fertilized eggs are monitored in the 
							lab for 3 to 5 days as they develop into embryos.</li>
						<li><strong>Embryo transfer:</strong> one embryo is placed into your uterus. 
							Any remaining viable embryos can be frozen for future use.</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="highlight-box">
				<strong>The Ontario Fertility Program funds one IVF cycle per eligible patient per lifetime.</strong>
				<ul class="highlight-box_list">
					<li>You must be an Ontario resident with a valid OHIP card and 
						<b class="navy-text">under the age of 43</b>.</li>
					<li>The funded cycle includes monitoring, egg retrieval, sperm preparation, 
						fertilization (including ICSI if needed), embryo development, fresh 
						embryo transfer, and embryo freezing.</li>
					<li>One cycle means one egg retrieval. If that retrieval produces multiple 
						embryos, you can transfer them one at a time until all viable embryos 
						from that cycle have been used.</li>
					<li>Fertility <b class="navy-text">medications are not covered</b> and 
						typically cost 
						<a href="https://www.ontario.ca/page/get-fertility-treatments" target="_blank" 
						class="green-text" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" 
						title="Source: Ontario Ministry of Health">
							<span class="orange-text">$5,000 per cycle</span></a>. 
						Some clinics report costs up to $10,000+ depending on your protocol.</li>
					<li>Genetic testing 
						(<span class="ohip-tip" data-bs-toggle="tooltip" 
							title="Pre-implantation Genetic Testing: screens embryos for chromosomal abnormalities or specific genetic conditions before transfer.">PGT</span>) 
						and long-term embryo storage are also not covered.</li>
					<li>If you act as a surrogate for another patient, you may receive one 
						additional funded cycle.</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</div>

		<%- include('partials/quiz-stage3') %>
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-between mt-5">
			<a href="<%= basePath %>/stage2" class="btn btn-outline-sage">← Stage 2: Investigative Cycle</a>
			<a href="<%= basePath %>/" class="btn btn-outline-sage">Back to Home</a>
		</div>
	</div>
</section>

</main>
<%- include('partials/footer.ejs') %>
